[Comparing the district specific list of cases presented in the above media report with that available on the End Polio Pakistan website, which is current since last week's global update (showing a total of 72 cases (see http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-district-wise-2019), there are 5 cases listed in the above newswire which do not reconcile with the official information. Clarification from knowledgeable sources would be greatly appreciated.

The story of the child developing paralysis after an intramuscular injection brought to mind the discussions on "provocation poliomyelitis." Borrowing from my previous moderator comment (see Poliomyelitis update (77): Pakistan (SD, PB, KP) 20190929.6700783): "Through the years, there have been observations and theories about "provocation poliomyelitis" where paralysis is "provoked" by trauma when an individual is infected with a poliovirus. A major concern was the receipt of intramuscular injections during the incubation period. Gromeier and Wimmer studied this in an animal model and observed that "Skeletal muscle injury induces retrograde axonal transport of poliovirus and thereby facilitates viral invasion of the central nervous system and the progression of spinal cord damage." Strebel et al did a case control study of vaccine associated polio cases in Romania and demonstrated that the same phenomenon was observed and associated with intramuscular injections within 30 days of receipt of oral poliovirus vaccine.

Refs.
1. Gromeier M, Wimmer E. Mechanism of injury-provoked poliomyelitis. J Virol. 1998 Jun;72(6):5056-60. full text available at https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC110068/.
2. Strebel PM, Ion-Nedelcu N, Baughman AL, Sutter RW, Cochi SL. N Engl J Med. 1995 Feb 23; 332(8):500-6. full text available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199502233320804."

Given the continued fairly widespread circulation of the WPV in Pakistan, it might seem prudent for clinicians to avoid giving IM injections to children presenting with "viral syndrome-like symptoms," as those symptoms may be due to poliovirus infection. - Mod.MPP]

